    "body": "## Purpose\n\n```bash\n[rank3]:[W310 15:54:45.576772833 ProcessGroupNCCL.cpp:1802] [PG ID 0 PG GUID 0 Rank 3] Failed to check the \"should dump\" flag on TCPStore, (maybe TCPStore server has shut down too early), with error: Failed to recv, got 0 bytes. Connection was likely closed. Did the remote server shutdown or crash?\n[rank1]:[W310 15:54:45.574839167 TCPStore.cpp:125] [c10d] recvValue failed on SocketImpl(fd=86, addr=[localhost]:54074, remote=[localhost]:43801): Failed to recv, got 0 bytes. Connection was likely closed. Did the remote server shutdown or crash?\nException raised from recvBytes at /pytorch/torch/csrc/distributed/c10d/Utils.hpp:682 (most recent call first):\nframe #0: c10::Error::Error(c10::SourceLocation, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> >) + 0x9d (0x7fd6cbd72fdd in /home/yewentao256/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/torch/lib/libc10.so)\nframe #1: <unknown function> + 0x6a3327d (0x7fd634c3327d in /home/yewentao256/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/torch/lib/libtorch_cpu.so)\nframe #2: c10d::TCPStore::check(std::vector<std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> >, std::allocator<std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > > > const&) + 0x273 (0x7fd634c31213 in /home/yewentao256/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/torch/lib/libtorch_cpu.so)\nframe #3: c10d::ProcessGroupNCCL::HeartbeatMonitor::runLoop() + 0x44c (0x7fd610b0af1c in /home/yewentao256/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/torch/lib/libtorch_cuda.so)\nframe #4: <unknown function> + 0xdbad4 (0x7fd69bcdbad4 in /lib64/libstdc++.so.6)\nframe #5: <unknown function> + 0x8a19a (0x7fd6cca8a19a in /lib64/libc.so.6)\nframe #6: <unknown function> + 0x10f100 (0x7fd6ccb0f100 in /lib64/libc.so.6)\n```\n\nvLLM workers seed Python's global RNG (commonly `seed=0`) during initialization. \n\nFlashInfer MNNVL uses `random.randint(...)` to generate an IPC `opId` used in socket names (`/tmp/mcastmem-socket-*`).\n\nWith concurrent jobs, deterministic RNG can produce identical `opId`s, leading to:\n- `Errno 98: Address already in use` during workspace creation on some ranks,\n- inconsistent collective state across ranks,\n- NCCL watchdog timeouts during initialization.\n\nThis PR fixes the issue.\n",
